[[Blaseball-Reference|https://blaseball-reference.com/]] displays "derived statistics" about players and teams, including leaderboards for various metrics. If you're coming from a baseball background, or want to understand actual past performance (as opposed to apple stats) it's invaluable. There's CSV exports as well for many pages, for you to use for your own analyses! It's brought to you by shibboh. [[Source code here.|https://github.com/mjhale/blaseball-reference.com]] <<include WhereToDiscuss>> Developer discussion is at @@.channel;#blaseball-reference@@ under 'Major Projects'.<<set $bot_choice to "Blasebot">> Blasebot has a bunch of interesting uses in terms of look ups and summaries of games sent directly to your server! <<if $blasebot_var is "lookup">><<include JoinUsForBots>><</if>> Check out the [[source code|https://github.com/BeeFox-sys/blasebot]]. <<if $blasebot_var is "alerts">> You'll find an invite link to the bot in the readme above, which you can use to get the bot set up in your own server. <<include WhereToDiscuss>> <</if>> If you'd like, you can also support Fox's efforts directly through stars' [[Patreon|https://www.patreon.com/beefox]].[[This site|https://blaseguids.azurewebsites.net/]] gives the unique IDs - long strings of letters and numbers - for teams and players. Particularly useful when dealing with [[APIs|NumberCrunchy]]. Brought to you by astory. <<include WhereToDiscuss>>[[Blases Loaded|https://blases-loaded.sibr.dev/#/tabs/about]] shows games in progress in a format that may feel familiar to those who follow baseball, with native mobile support. It's brought to you by RangerRick. Get the [[iOS app|https://apps.apple.com/us/app/id1529695719]] or [[Android app|https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.raccoonfink.blobile]] if those are relevant to you! Source code, links to beta builds, and issue tracking [[here|https://github.com/RangerRick/blobile]]. <<include WhereToDiscuss>>[[Chartographer|https://chartographer.sibr.dev/]] has a number of ways to compare teams against each other in the current season - the sums and averages of team stars in each of the categories, as well as Win/Loss graphs. It's brought to you by Cheeseyx. Note if you want something similar to the "Team Averages" scatterplots but over time, there's a nice viewer in [[Edgarware's Jupyter Notebooks|Notebooks]]. <<include WhereToDiscuss>>[[ChartParty|http://yoori.space/chartparty]] plots win/loss charts for teams, including the option to look at past seasons. It's brought to you by yooori. <<include WhereToDiscuss>><<set $discussion_channel to "chronicler">> Chronicler brings together game events and other data from the [[official API|OfficialAPI]] into a form that makes historical comparisons easier. It's brought to you by Astrid. API documentation [[here|https://astrid.stoplight.io/docs/sibr/reference/Chronicler.v1.yaml]]. Like for the official API, you can also use the {{{csv.sibr.dev}}} tool - you can replace an {{{api.sibr.dev}}} URL with {{{csv.sibr.dev}}} if that's a better format for you than JSON. There will always be some delay between updates on the official API and Chronicler. If you need events in an at-bat as opposed to per-pitch format, you're better off using [[Datablase]]. If you'd like to use Python, [[there's a wrapper available|Mike]]. If you'd like more robust search of the S12-onwards Feed, you're probably better off using [[Eventually]]. <<include WhereToDiscuss>> If you'd like, you can also support Astrid's efforts directly through her [[Patreon|https://www.patreon.com/floofstrid]].The Monitor watches for cycles, perfect games, and the like. It's brought to you by tehstone. <<include JoinUsForBots>> You can also Follow it on your own server for your own alerts! Check out the [[source for the bot|https://github.com/tehstone/blaseballwatcher/]].<<set $discussion_channel to "💽-datablase">> The ''Datablase'' is our fancy name for a stack of technology that does the following: 1) Ingest raw data from [[Chronicler]] 2) Change it from individual-pitch events to per-atbat events 3) Store it in a PostgreSQL DB 4) Expose API endpoints for the DB <<include WhereToDiscuss>> [[Learn more about how it works or contribute to it|Contributing]] [[Get some data from it by using an API endpoint|DatablaseApi]] [[Get some data from it by handcrafting my own artisanal SQL queries|GuestAccess]]The two major Github projects that constitute the Datablase are: [[Prophesizer|https://github.com/Society-for-Internet-Blaseball-Research/prophesizer]] C# application that parses raw game updates into game events describing all the pitches that happened during an at-bat (mostly). [[Datablase|https://github.com/Society-for-Internet-Blaseball-Research/datablase]] Javascript application that exposes API endpoints for fetching DB information. [[blaseball-reference.com|BlaseballReference]] uses these APIs to drive its content. For more information on any of these, visit the @@.channel;#💽-datablase@@ channel on the SIBR Discord. You'll need access to the '💼 Major Projects' role in @@.channel;#roles-and-sigils@@ to see it. [[Back to Datablase|Datablase]]Documentation for the Datablase API can be found at https://api.blaseball-reference.com/docs#/ [[Back to Datablase|Datablase]]We have a PGadmin setup for writing your own queries! Instructions on guest access are [[here|https://docs.sibr.dev/docs/apis/docs/z-datablase-guest-access.md]]. Brought to you by hexane. $discussion_channel to "eventuallie">> Eventually is a small search engine API for the blaseball feed (Seasons 12 onwards), allowing you to search through it with as much or as little specificity as you want. Want to find every interaction between NaN and Forrest Best? [[Yep, you can do it!|https://api.sibr.dev/eventually/events?playerNames=Forrest%20Best_NaN]] You can find API documentation [[here|https://allie-signet.stoplight.io/docs/eventually/reference/eventually-api.v1.yaml]], or use the [[blaseball_mike wrapper for python|Mike]]. You can also use the {{{csv.sibr.dev}}} tool - you can replace an {{{api.sibr.dev}}} URL with {{{csv.sibr.dev}}} if that's a better format for you than JSON. If you're looking for pre-S12 game events, you're probably better off using [[Chronicler]]. It's made by allie (sapphicfettucine#6248), and you can find the source code on [[this github repo|https://github.com/alisww/eventually]] <<include WhereToDiscuss>>There are a lot of [[Falsehoods Programmers Believe about Blaseball|https://sibr.dev/falsehoods]]. [[Source here|https://github.com/kawa-kitsuragi/whichtool]]. <<include WhereToDiscuss>><<set $discussion_channel to "ch00bs-cursed-projects">> [[blaseball_mike|https://jmaliksi.github.io/blaseball-mike/]] is a Python wrapper for the [[official API|OfficialAPI]], [[Chronicler]], [[Eventually]], and (partially) [[Datablase]]. Brought to you by ch00beh and Edgarware. Source code [[here|https://github.com/jmaliksi/blaseball-mike]]. <<include WhereToDiscuss>>[[These graphs|https://edgarware.github.io/blaseball_notebooks/star_average.html]] show team average stars changing over time. It's brought to you by Edgarware. Source [[here|https://github.com/Edgarware/blaseball_notebooks/blob/main/misc_notebooks/star_average.ipynb]]. Elsewhere in that repository are other Jupyter notebooks that may be of interest, mostly involving past elections, and a great [[tutorial|https://edgarware.github.io/blaseball_notebooks/tutorial.html]] on how to make your own!You can extract data directly from the API that powers blaseball.com itself. Since this is the data that powers the website, it's the fastest source for at-the-moment updates. We've discovered a number of endpoints and try to collect documentation [[here|https://docs.sibr.dev/docs/apis/reference/Blaseball-API.v1.yaml]]. Discussion about finding and using these endpoints generally happens at @@.channel;#blaseball-api@@. You'll need the '📖 Research' role in @@.channel;#roles-and-sigils@@ to see this channel. We also have a [[CORS proxy|https://cors-proxy.blaseball-reference.com/]] available for you, as well as a CSV redirect: you can replace a {{{blaseball.com}}} URL with {{{csv.sibr.dev}}} if that's a better format for you than JSON. The major caveat to using this is that endpoints tend to give current data, not historical data, on a per-game-event basis. [[Chronicler]] is your best bet for past events on that per-game-event basis, and [[Datablase]] is your choice collapsing game events to at-bats. It can also be hard to compare things across teams in some cases, where our downstream APIs will serve you better. Feel free to ask in @@.channel;#❓-help-desk@@ in 'The Society' for API help![[Onomancer|https://onomancer.sibr.dev]] collects potential blaseball names, generates apple stats (and derived stars etc) for those names, and lets you rate them and collect them into custom teams. It's brought to you by ch00beh. It includes an API for using these names in your own projects. Source code [[here|https://github.com/jmaliksi/onomancer]]. <<include WhereToDiscuss>>The current "best source" for apple stats (such as divinity and shakesperianism) is [[this player viewer|https://blaseballplayers.netlify.app/]]. It features robust searching and filtering, the ability to save subsets of players for easy comparison, as well as noting additions/subtractions due to items in italics. It's brought to you by Astrid, and it's currently a work in progress. [[Contribute to the source here|https://github.com/xSke/blaseball-player-list]]. <<include WhereToDiscuss>> If you'd like, you can also support Astrid's efforts directly through her [[Patreon|https://www.patreon.com/floofstrid]]. Notably, the newest player viewer currently does not have alternate color schemes for colorblindness. If you require that before this is added, try [[Abslve|https://slavfox.space/abslve/#SUN]] or [[the original viewer|https://stlats.sibr.dev]], but neither are in active development and may have unusual behavior (e.g. including Coffee Cup teams mixed with ILB teams, not reflecting items).[[Blaseball Playoff Status|https://mixolyde.net/blaseballstatus/index.html]] breaks down the current season's status regarding playoff positions and "Party Time" (needs more than 1 Win per game to make the playoffs). It's brought to you by Mixolyde. [[Source code here|https://github.com/mixolyde/blaseballstatus]]. <<include WhereToDiscuss>>[[Reblase|https://reblase.sibr.dev]] collects past game logs, future schedules, and points where players change. Brought to you by Astrid. [[Here's the source code.|https://github.com/Society-for-Internet-Blaseball-Research/Reblase]] <<set $discussion_channel to "reblase">> <<include WhereToDiscuss>> If you'd like, you can also support Astrid's efforts directly through her [[Patreon|https://www.patreon.com/floofstrid]].[[Renovations.SIBR.dev|https://renovations.sibr.dev/]] is a web visualizer to show all current and past know stadium renovation modifications, as well as to show current ballpark stats, without needing to flute between teams or purchase a pizza concession. It's brought to you by Dlareau. All known renovations across all teams are shown at the top, and you can hover over a renovation or a ballpark stat (once expanded) to see what it does. These expanded ballpark stats are mild FK potentially, as the current Blaseball.com website does not display specific values for these visually. <<include WhereToDiscuss>>Welcome to the Salmon Institute for Blaseball Research. you can find us at @@.channel;#crisp@@ under '🐟 Salmon', and you'll need the matching role in @@.channel;#roles-and-sigils@@ to see it. [[This smells fishy. What is it all about?|SteveWriteup]] [[Tell me how good a blaseball player is at managing salmon fisheries|Yuuko]] [[I want to use python to run salmon simulations|salmon_lib]] [[I want to use an API to run salmon simulations|webcrisp]] [[I want to explore the original source|crisp_src]]There are many ways to enjoy blaseball—all valid. Some fans simply bet on matches. Others eagerly discuss their favorite teams and generate entire backstories for their players. There are fans who compile statistics, or draw fan art, or both. [[And some fans uncover hidden secrets in 25-year-old salmon modeling software.|https://salmon.sibr.dev/steve.html]] Honu discussed the salmon saga on Blaseball Sunday, if you prefer to [[listen to the interview|https://youtu.be/L2poaPBgRmg?t=3065]].SIBR's salmon sages have the tool for you: [[salmon_lib|https://github.com/Society-for-Internet-Blaseball-Research/salmon_lib]]We built a JSON API for 1995 salmon software. [[You can find it here.|https://github.com/Society-for-Internet-Blaseball-Research/webcrisp]]The University of Washington School of Fisheries Columbia Basin Research Group very generously sent us the code for CRiSP Harvest v 3.0.6, which we have [[mirrored on Github for research and archival|https://github.com/Society-for-Internet-Blaseball-Research/crisp]]. Due to particular C++ dependencies, it currently does not compile - if you have any resources on RogueWave, please get in touch with us in @@.channel;#crisp@@! **Please keep in mind:** [[Salmon Steve|SteveWriteup]]'s identity is in this code. We can't, like, edit that out, but out of respect to his privacy please avoid including mentioning his last name, beyond the first initial. Steve U. is fine.Salmon, under Salmon Weather (as of Season 15), steal runs by swimming upstream. [[This page|https://hora.github.io/blaseball-scoreboard/]] shows every game the salmon were in, and how many runs they took, as if they were a third team on the field. A white triangle indicates the ILB winner of the game; a pink triangle notes that the salmon had more Runs than at least one ILB team. Brought to you by Dawn T. <<include WhereToDiscuss>>A new blaseball final score is called [[Sclorigami|https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1ITCtaZAXimgO7bjPaBeb3w_n9R20cEH07kIsSFJEj90/edit#gid=0]]! You'll need the matching role from @@.channel;#roles-and-sigils@@ to see it.[[The Stadium Viewer|https://stadium-viewer.sibr.dev/]] renders blaseball stadiums based on their renovations and properties (such as grandiosity). On desktop, use WASD to rotate the stadium in space, and R+F for zooming. It's brought to you by Rose. [[Source here|https://github.com/RosaryMala/BlaseballStadiumViewer]]. <<include WhereToDiscuss>>[[Tome|https://tome.sibr.dev/]] shows the results of each player's at bat and basic pitcher performance stats (e.g. number of strikeouts) in a given game. Brought to you by iliana and ch00beh. New features are in progress, to make this a tool for broadcasters. Source code [[here|https://github.com/Society-for-Internet-Blaseball-Research/tome]]. <<include WhereToDiscuss>>[[Blaseball Compact|https://thevdude.github.io/BlaseballCompact/]] is a Stylus userstyle to fit blaseball games during the regular season in a 3 x 4 grid. Consumer Contrast (at the same link) makes CONSUMERS stand out more on the page. Both are brought to you by theVdude. [[Emoji fix|https://holmesmr.github.io/Blaseball-Userstyles/]] is another Stylus userstyle to fix the emoji of the Spies, Fridays, and Mechs, and un-ORBs the Talkers. It's brought to you by Cepheus. Note that the 'BIG SCREEN BLASEBALL' style on this page is a prereq to Compact, but was not updated to fit the 2 extra games per day that were started in Season 13. [[Blaseball+|https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/blaseball-plus/]] adds functionality such as [[Reblase]] and [[Abslve|PlayerViewers]] links for Firefox. It's brought to you by leo60228.[[VibeCheck|https://vibecheck.sibr.dev/]] plots player vibes by day based on our knowledge of the vibe formula. It attemps to do a collective team vibe as well, but currently doesn't reflect pitcher rotations correctly. It's brought to you by dlareau. Its source code is [[here|https://github.com/Society-for-Internet-Blaseball-Research/vibecheck]].The [[Wall of Time|https://www.enbyss.com/content/tools/blaseball-time]] shows countdowns to the various points of the blaseball season, and lets you get browser notifications close to when they happen.
